This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with object classification and occlusion in images. The use of deep convolutional neural networks (DCNNs) also suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the use of compositional models and mixtures of models suggests that it could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of clustering and dictionaries also suggests that it could belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the use of experimental results suggests that it could belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
